       <Markdown>
            # Writing Process Journal 2
            ## Introduction
            
            One of the myths about writing is that people are either born good or bad writers,
            but research tells us that "writing requires practice for everyone, and all writers
            have more to learn" (Wardle and Downs 12). Yet if your teachers thought of writing
            like an innate talent rather than a learned skill, then you may have received feedback
            that reinforced the idea that you were born a good or bad writer. In fact, one of the
            threshold concepts _Writing About Writing_ introduces is, "writing is influenced by
            identities and prior experiences" (Wardle and Downs 12). Our experiences with writing
            start very early, and each time we encounter a new writing task, we come to that task
            with identities formed by all our prior experiences.            
            
            In this assignment, you'll reflect about the experiences that have shaped your
            understanding of what writing is, what makes someone a good writer, and how people
            learn to write well. 
            
            To complete this assignment, you will:
            
            - **Part 1**: Write about an experience that shaped your identity as a writer.
            - **Part 2**: Complete a survey that will help you reflect on your writing priorities.
            - **Part 3**: Define what you think good writing is, and explain how people can become better writers.
            - **Part 4**: Complete a self-evaluation form. What are your strengths and weaknesses as a writer?
       </Markdown>
    </Vertical>
